  <mainDescription>&lt;h4&gt;
    Detail flow of events
&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    As a starting point, use&amp;nbsp;the step-by-step description of the use-case flow of events created as mentioned in &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../basic_unified_process/guidances/guidelines/find_and_outline_actors_and_ucs,_eyL0wCu-EdqSxKAVa9kmvA.html&quot; guid=&quot;_eyL0wCu-EdqSxKAVa9kmvA&quot;&gt;Guideline: Find and Outline Actors and Use Cases&lt;/a&gt;. Then, gradually add details to
    the flow of events, describing what is done in the Use Case, not how problems internal to the system should be solved.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    A flow of events descritption explores:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        How and when the Use Case starts
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        When the use case interacts with the actors, and what data they exchange
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        How and when the use case uses data stored in the system, or stores data in the system
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        How and when the use case ends
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    For more information, see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../basic_unified_process/guidances/guidelines/use_case,_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw.html&quot; guid=&quot;_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw&quot;&gt;Guideline: Use Case&lt;/a&gt;, the discussion on &lt;u&gt;contents&lt;/u&gt; and &lt;u&gt;style&lt;/u&gt; of the flow
    of events.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;
    Structure flow of events
&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    A use case's flow of events can be divided into several subflows. These optional or alternative flows must be
    described.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    Unless&amp;nbsp;a subflow involves only a minor part of the complete flow of events -- which can be described&amp;nbsp;in the
    body of the text -- it is recommended that you describe each subflow in a separate supplement to the Flow of Events
    section, being mandatory for the following cases:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        Subflows that occupy a large segment of a given flow of events.
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        Exceptional flows of events. This helps the use case's basic flow of events to stand out more clearly.
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        Any subflow that can be executed at several intervals in the same flow of events.
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    For more information, see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../basic_unified_process/guidances/guidelines/use_case,_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw.html&quot; guid=&quot;_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw&quot;&gt;Guideline: Use Case&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;u&gt;Structure of the Flow of Events&lt;/u&gt; section.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;
    Describe special requirements
&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    Any requirements that can be related to the use case, but that are not taken into consideration in the Flow of Events
    of the use case, should be described in the Special Requirements of the use case. Such requirements are likely to be
    nonfunctional.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    Typically, Supplemental Requirements which refer to a specific Use Case are captured in the Special
    Requirements&amp;nbsp;section.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    For more information, see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../basic_unified_process/guidances/guidelines/use_case,_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw.html&quot; guid=&quot;_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw&quot;&gt;Guideline: Use Case&lt;/a&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;Special Requirements&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;section.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;
    Describe preconditions and postconditions
&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    A precondition on a use case explains the state the system must be in order for the use case to be possible to start.
    Take care to describe the system state. Avoid describing the detail of other incidental activities that may have taken
    place prior to this use case.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    A postcondition on a use case lists possible states the system can be in at the end of the use case. The system must be
    in one of those states at the end of the execution of the use case. It is also used to state actions that the system
    performs at the end of the use case, regardless of what occurred in the use case.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    Neither preconditions nor postconditions are not used to create a sequence of use cases. As a general rule, there will
    never be a case where you have to first perform one use case, then another, in order to have a meaningful flow of
    events. If that is the case, correct the problem by reviewing the use cases were&amp;nbsp;decomposed. See step &lt;u&gt;Structure
    flow of Events&lt;/u&gt; and &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../basic_unified_process/guidances/guidelines/use_case,_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw.html&quot; guid=&quot;_0Ve10MlgEdmt3adZL5Dmdw&quot;&gt;Guideline: Use Case&lt;/a&gt;&lt;u&gt;,&lt;/u&gt; &lt;u&gt;Preconditions and Post Conditions&lt;/u&gt; section.
&lt;/p&gt;
